{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/keyword-spotting-embedded-on-the-arm-cortex-m0-69241f69fde3", "time": 1683002775.565422, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/keyword-spotting-embedded-on-the-arm-cortex-m0-69241f69fde3/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to Implement Cough Detection on the Arm Cortex-M0 | by Kofi Odame | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to Implement Cough Detection on the Arm Cortex-M0", "description": "Deep neural networks (DNNs) have an unparalleled ability to extract high-level information (like, \u201cHow many times has a patient coughed in the past hour?\u201d) from raw sensor data. But DNNs are\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://sites.dartmouth.edu/odame/research/asthma-symptom-monitoring/", "anchor_text": "papers", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["Deep neural networks (DNNs) have an unparalleled ability to extract high-level information (like, \u201cHow many times has a patient coughed in the past hour?\u201d) from raw sensor data.", "But DNNs are typically implemented in the cloud, as they are too resource intensive for embedded microcontrollers. This leaves embedded systems engineers with an uncomfortable choice: either (1) transmit data from the sensor to cloud-based neural networks and pay the price of short battery life, poor latency and threats to data privacy, or (2) forego the powerful inference capabilities of deep neural networks.", "Current \u201cedge AI\u201d solutions to this problem rely on heavy-duty microprocessors and DSPs, but these can burn anywhere from 0.5 W to 30 W of power. They are impractical for a light, unobtrusive wearable device for cough counting that barely has 10 mW to spare.", "In this article, we describe a few tricks for squeezing deep neural networks into resource constrained platforms like the ultra low-power ARM Cortex-M0+ microcontroller.", "Our approach is based on the embedded Gated Recurrent Unit (eGRU), which exploits a number of modifications (see Fig. 1) that we will now consider in turn.", "The eGRU has an update gate but no reset gate. This reduces the model\u2019s footprint by a third. Now, without a reset gate, the eGRU is prone to latch-up when presented with certain large inputs. This challenge is mitigated during backpropagation training: during the forward pass of each iteration, the eGRU states are initialized from a uniform random distribution. This forces the eGRU to discard past memory whenever any new, relevant data is presented.", "The Cortex-M0+ has no dedicated floating point unit, making the softsign a desirable alternative to the conventional GRU\u2019s tanh and sigmoid activation functions. The rectified linear unit (ReLU) is an even more efficient activation function, but combining ReLU with heavily-quantized weights would ruin the network\u2019s performance. So, softsign is a good compromise: its saturating property helps maintain network performance, and it runs more than 10X faster than either the tanh or sigmoid on the M0+.", "The eGRU stores its weights with a 3-bit exponential quantization code, reducing the network\u2019s footprint by 10X.", "To conform to the M0+ 32-bit architecture, the eGRU performs all arithmetic using the Q15 16-bit fixed point format. Weight multiplications, the most frequent operations, are implemented as right-shift operations thanks to the exponential weight quantization. This contributes to a 20X increase in speed.", "The eGRU has been evaluated on three Acoustic Event Detection (AED) tasks of varying complexity: cough detection, spoken digit recognition, and urban sounds recognition (see Fig. 2).", "Compared to a traditional GRU implemented on a workstation, the eGRU implemented on an ARM Cortex-M0+ performs comparably well on cough detection, and slightly worse on the spoken digits task. The eGRU\u2019s performance on the urban sounds task is substantially worse than the traditional GRU\u2019s (see Fig. 3).", "As it currently stands, the eGRU is effective for short acoustic event detection or keyword spotting tasks embedded on a low power microcontroller unit.", "Interested in sources? Check out our original research papers.", "Interested in tea? This article pairs well with Earl Grey.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I am an Associate Professor of Engineering at Dartmouth College, with interests in circuit design, embedded systems and nonlinear signal processing."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F69241f69fde3&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkeyword-spotting-embedded-on-the-arm-cortex-m0-69241f69fde3&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkeyword-spotting-embedded-on-the-arm-cortex-m0-69241f69fde3&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fkeyword-spotting-embedded-on-the-arm-cortex-m0-69241f69fde3&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------",